{#- Categories + tags for the post sidebar.
    Both taxonomies are separate archives (/category/<slug>/ and /tag/<slug>/);
    the terms are slugged here with the `slug` filter, which is a thin alias over
    the built-in `slugify` — the SAME function eleventy.config.js uses to build
    the archive permalinks, so these links cannot drift out of sync.

    `publicTags` strips the internal terms (posts, all, featured, page) — a post's
    `tags` always carries "posts" (that is how the collection is built), and
    "featured" can appear in either taxonomy, so BOTH lists are filtered through it.

    Each block renders only when it has terms left after filtering: no empty
    headings, no stray separators on the 40 posts that have no categories. -#}
{%- set postCategories = post.data.categories | publicTags %}
{%- set postTags = post.data.tags | publicTags %}

{%- if postCategories.length or postTags.length %}
<div class="gh-article-taxonomy">
	{%- if postCategories.length %}
	<div class="gh-article-terms">
		<h2 class="gh-article-terms-title">{{ "Categories" | t }}</h2>
		<ul class="gh-article-terms-list">
			{%- for term in postCategories %}
			<li><a class="gh-article-term" href="/category/{{ term | slug }}/">{{ term }}</a></li>
			{%- endfor %}
		</ul>
	</div>
	{%- endif %}

	{%- if postTags.length %}
	<div class="gh-article-terms">
		<h2 class="gh-article-terms-title">{{ "Tags" | t }}</h2>
		<ul class="gh-article-terms-list">
			{%- for term in postTags %}
			<li><a class="gh-article-term" href="/tag/{{ term | slug }}/">{{ term }}</a></li>
			{%- endfor %}
		</ul>
	</div>
	{%- endif %}
</div>
{%- endif %}
